Project Name: The Relationship Between Social Media Use, Anxiety, and Relationship Satisfaction. 
Principal Investigator: Jayde Onori
Popular Music Major 
William Paterson University 
College of Arts & Communication 
201-708-5563 onorij@student.wpunj.edu  
Voluntary participation: Your participation is voluntary and at any time during the study, you have the right to refuse to answer questions or discontinue your participation in this survey without penalty. 
Duration: The experiment will last no longer than 15 minutes. 
Risks and Benefits: There are no risks associated with this study beyond what would be encountered in normal life. All data will be collected anonymously. If you find some of the questions to be sensitive or experience any emotional discomfort, refer to the contact information provided below for help. 
Statement of Confidentiality: Your participation in this research is confidential. No personally identifiable information will be stored with your data, and data will be stored on a password protected computer. 
Purpose of the Research: The purpose of this research study is to determine whether high social media use reduces relationship satisfaction by increasing anxiety. 
General Plan of the Research: In this survey, you will be asked to respond to a series of scales and personal questions. After each question is presented, you will be asked to answer the following question or complete the following scale. After the survey, you are encouraged to ask questions about this research and your rights as a participant. Contact information is included below, and you may voice any concerns and report any study-related problems.                                                    
Right to Ask Questions: If you have any questions concerning this research project, you should contact Jayde Onori at 201-708-5563 or by email at onorij@student.wpunj.edu. If you experienced any emotional discomfort that you wish to address to someone other than the investigator, you may contact William Paterson’s Counseling Services at 973-720-2257. You must be 18 years of age or older to take part in this research study.
